SIMPLE: pinion
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pinion
<hw>Pin"ion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A
moth of the genus <gen>Lithophane</gen>, as <spn>Lithophane
antennata</spn>, whose larva bores large holes in young peaches and
apples.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pinion</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pinion
<hw>Pin"ion</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>pignon</ets> a pen, F.,
gable, pinion (in sense 5); cf. Sp. <ets>pi⟦ntil⟧on</ets> pinion; fr. L.
<ets>pinna</ets> pinnacle, feather, wing. See <er>Pin</er> a peg, and
cf. <er>Pen</er> a feather, <er>Pennat</er>, <er>Pennon</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A feather; a quill.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A wing, literal or figurative.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Swift on his sooty <qex>pinions</qex> flits the gnome.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The joint of bird's wing most remote from the
body.</def> <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A fetter for the arm.</def>
<rj><au>Ainsworth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>A cogwheel with a small number of
teeth, or leaves, adapted to engage with a larger wheel, or rack (see
<er>Rack</er>); esp., such a wheel having its leaves formed of the
substance of the arbor or spindle which is its axis.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Lantern pinion</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Lantern</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Pinion wire</b></col>, <cd>wire fluted
longitudinally, for making the pinions of clocks and watches. It is
formed by being drawn through holes of the shape required for the leaves
or teeth of the pinions.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pinion</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Pinion
<hw>Pin"ion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Pinioned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Pinioning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bind or
confine the wings of; to confine by binding the wings.</def>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To disable by cutting off the pinion joint.</def>
<rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To disable or restrain, as a person, by binding the
arms, esp. by binding the arms to the body.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her elbows <qex>pinioned</qex> close upon her hips.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Hence, generally, to confine; to bind; to tie
up.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Pinioned</xex> up by formal rules of state.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Norris.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pinioned</ent>⟦br⟧
